item.title: Difference between exons and introns
item.description: What is an exon and intron? Introns are noncoding sections of an RNA transcript, or the DNA encoding it, that are spliced out before the RNA molecule is translated into a protein. The sections of DNA (or RNA) that code for proteins are called exons. What are two significant differences between introns and exons? item.title: What is the significance of the two membranes which surround the lungs
item.description: What are the two membranes surrounding the lungs? The pleura includes two thin layers of tissue that protect and cushion the lungs. The inner layer (visceral pleura) wraps around the lungs and is stuck so tightly to the lungs that it cannot be peeled off. The outer layer (parietal pleura) lines the inside of the chest wall. Why is it important that there are two pleural membranes? Each pleural cavity and it‚Äôs enclosed lung are lined by a serous membrane called pleura.

item.title: Russian and U.S. Space Legends Meet 40 Years After 'Handshake in Space' (Video)
item.description: Friday marks 40 years since the first docking of two spacecraft designed and built by two different nations as part of the Apollo-Soyuz mission. The joint mission by the United States and Soviet Union was a high symbol of detente, marking the end of the Cold War space race and the foundation of today's 15-nation International Space Station (ISS). Pitched by President Richard Nixon in 1972, the mission launched on July 15, 1975. Two spacecraft took off from opposite ends of the earth ‚Äî the Kennedy Space Center in Florida and the ultra-secret Soviet cosmodrome in Baikonur, Kazakhstan.
